# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-pinkwart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 22 September 2002 to elect the members of the 15th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Incumbent Chancellor Gerhard Schröder's centre-left "red-green" governing coalition retained a narrow majority, and the Social Democratic Party (SPD) retained their status as the largest party in the Bundestag by three seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Several issues dominated the campaign, with the opposition CDU/CSU attacking the government's performance on the economy which fell back into recession due to the Telecoms crash and the introduction of the euro, as well as campaigning on family values and against taxes (particularly on fuel).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] However, event soon overtook Stoiber and the CDU/CSU campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] The SPD and the Greens were helped by broad support for its opposition to an invasion of Iraq, continued media attention on the CDU funding scandal and by Gerhard Schröder's personal popularity relative to the opposition's candidate for chancellor, Stoiber.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] The SPD was also boosted by Schröder's swift response to the August floods in eastern Germany, as compared to Stoiber, who was on vacation and responded late to the events.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] With Guido Westerwelle, leader of the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the FDP presented a chancellor candidate for the first time, usually a title reserved for the main election leaders of the SPD and CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] This was met with general derision and Westerwelle was excluded from the chancellor television debate, the first one, against which he unsuccessfully sued.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] After a brief honeymoon period, the CDU/CSU overtook the SPD in opinion polling in early 1999.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] This dramatically reversed after the CDU donations scandal, and the SPD established a strong lead which it held throughout 2000 and 2001.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU retook first place at the beginning of election year, and combined with a strong FDP, the opposition held a clear lead over the SPD–Green incumbents through mid-August.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Schröder's response to the floods that month buoyed the SPD's numbers, and put the CDU/CSU, FDP, and PDS on a downward trend.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Polling during the final week of the campaign gave a narrow edge of the SPD, but also indicated the FDP would finish ahead of the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Meanwhile, it was unclear if the PDS would win proportional seats, leaving the final outcome on a knife's edge.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Although most opposition parties gained seats, and the result was in doubt for most of the election night, the governing coalition retained a narrow majority.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] In particular, the SPD was able to partially offset declines in their vote share in the West with an increase in the East, with the PDS falling below both the 5% threshold and the 3-seat threshold, either of which is required to qualify a party for top-up seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] Consequently, the PDS held only two directly elected seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] The coalition between the SPD and the Greens continued in government, with Schröder as chancellor.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2002-german-federal-election] However, due to the slim majority in the Bundestag, the governing coalition was not stable.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The **2010 North Rhine-Westphalia state election** was held on 9 May 2010 to elect the 15th Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The outgoing government was a coalition of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and Free Democratic Party (FDP) led by Minister-President Jürgen Rüttgers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The election was a defeat for the incumbent government, but failed to produce a clear outcome.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU suffered its worst-ever result, falling over ten percentage points to just 34.6%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Hannelore Kraft also recorded a decline and finished just 0.1% behind the CDU; both parties tied on 67 seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens recorded their best result to date with 12%, while the FDP achieved a small swing to 6.7%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The newly-formed Left party won 5.6% and 11 seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Neither the incumbent CDU–FDP government (80 seats) or prospective SDP–Green coalition (90 seats) achieved a majority in the Landtag, with The Left narrowly holding balance of power.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Complex talks took place between all five parties, with the CDU and SPD each aiming for a coalition with the Greens and FDP, or a grand coalition between the two of them.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD and Greens also held talks with The Left.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] All discussions ended without success by mid-June.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] On the 17th, the SPD and Greens announced they would attempt to form a minority government led by Hannelore Kraft.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They ruled out a confidence arrangement with The Left, but nonetheless relied on the party's abstention for the government's investiture to succeed.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Kraft was elected Minister-President on 14 July on the second ballot, which required only a simple majority, with 90 votes in favour, 80 against, and eleven abstentions.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Landtag is elected via mixed-member proportional representation.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 128 members are elected in single-member constituencies via first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 53 members are then allocated using compensatory proportional representation.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Voters have two votes: the "first vote" for candidates in single-member constituencies, and the "second vote" for party lists, which are used to fill the remaining seats in a way that achieves proportionality overall.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The minimum size of the Landtag is 181 members, but if overhang seats are present, proportional leveling seats will be added to ensure proportionality.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] An electoral threshold of 5% of valid votes is applied to the Landtag; parties that fall below this threshold are ineligible to receive seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This was the first state election in which voters had two votes.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In the previous election held on 22 May 2005, the SPD suffered a landslide defeat and was ousted from government for the first time since 1966.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They received only 37% of votes while the CDU emerged in a strong first place with almost 45%; the FDP and Greens each took 6%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU and FDP subsequently formed a coalition government under Jürgen Rüttgers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 14th Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] A total of 25 parties ran state lists in the election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Due to the newly-introduced two vote system, parties were able to stand their lists on ballots statewide without running candidates in every constituency, as had been the case previously.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 1,000 signatures were required for a party to run a state list.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In addition to the parties running lists, some stood only constituency candidates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] A number of independent candidates also ran.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Education policy was an important topic in the election campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The government wanted to retain the existing three-tier school system, and pointed out that during their tenure attendance had improved and many new teaching positions had been created.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The opposition criticised the state's poor performance in PISA studies, and campaigned for the establishment of schools which integrated more younger and older students to improve efficiency, as well as the abolition of tuition fees.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU was embroiled in a financing scandal in the lead up to the campaign, with companies accused of paying bribes in exchange for meetings with Minister-President Rüttgers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] A Bundestag investigation found no violation of party finance laws.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Shortly before the election, another scandal surfaced in which the CDU was accused of covertly commissioning a voters' initiative from a non-partisan communications agency, with the fundraising money allegedly used to pay for pro-Rüttgers newspaper ads under non-party branding.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The allegations were sourced from intercepted emails from the NRW CDU and published mostly anonymously online.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU lodged a complaint with the state prosecutor over data breaches, but attributed the accusations to a malicious defamation campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Federal issues also impacted the campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] A new federal coalition of the CDU and FDP had taken office about six months earlier.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] If the state government was defeated, the federal government would lose its majority in the Bundesrat, the upper house whose members mirror the composition of each state government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This could prevent the government from implementing some of its proposed projects, including a controversial possible extension to the lifespan of some nuclear power plants, which the SPD and Greens pointed out.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The federal government also delayed releasing its tax and budget plans until after the state election, which was widely criticised as a political play to avoid backlash from anticipated spending cuts.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Just a few weeks before the election, the government also agreed to help finance a €110 billion EU bailout of the Greek government-debt crisis.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Left also campaigned heavily on federal issues, criticising the social policy of both the federal CDU and former SPD governments, ongoing German involvement in the War in Afghanistan, and the consequences of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Despite being mostly a federal responsibility, employment and labour policy were also an important issue in the election; the left-wing opposition parties called for the establishment of a minimum wage, which the CDU and FDP opposed.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Both Rüttgers and Kraft distanced themselves from controversial federal social policy such as the Hartz IV programme.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Polls ahead of the election indicated that The Left was likely to enter the Landtag, while the two major parties were likely to suffer losses collectively.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This continued the trend in recent years of dwindling support for the traditional parties and an increasingly fractured parliamentary landscape with difficult majorities.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The FDP was the only party to commit to a single option to the exclusion of all others: a continuation of the incumbent government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU also campaigned to continue the coalition, but left the option of cooperation with the Greens open.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD expressed a preference for a coalition with the Greens but otherwise refused to draw hard lines.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens favoured the SPD, but likewise did not rule out working with the CDU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Relations with The Left were a sticking point: the CDU and FDP viewed cooperation as impossible, while the Greens and SPD left their options more open.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] However, the Greens did rule out a confidence and supply arrangement, and the SPD regularly denounced them as incapable of governing.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] For their part, The Left stated their willingness to join a coalition with the SPD and Greens and support Hannelore Kraft as Minister-President.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Due to the electoral reform that took place in this election, no swing is given for the constituency vote except for independents.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Swing values for the party list vote are compared to the single vote from the 2005 election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Exit polling by Forschungsgruppe Wahlen indicated that state politics was primary for most voters.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 55% said it was most important in their voting decision, while 41% said federal politics was more important, and only 15% said their vote was a protest against the federal government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] An overwhelming majority of voters (78%) named education as an important issue, alongside the Greek debt crisis (56%).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Only 38% considered CDU finance scandals important.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] According to Infratest dimap polling, economic development, education, and budget deficits were the most important issues.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD was considered more competent in the areas of education and social welfare, while the CDU led in economics and finance.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Compared to the 2005 election, while the issue of employment lost salience, perception of the SPD's competence in the area recovered while the CDU's declined.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Jürgen Rüttgers had particularly poor personal ratings.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Forschungsgruppe Wahlen found that only 40% of voters preferred him as Minister-President compared to 43% for Hannelore Kraft, an unusual result in Germany where incumbents are typically favoured over challengers, even in close elections.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Kraft was rated as more persuasive, sympathetic, and in-touch.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Nonetheless, a majority of voters placed more importance on programme and policy when voting, with only one-sixth choosing the lead candidates as the decisive factor.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU and SPD did poorly among young voters, who voted strongly for the Greens and non-parliamentary minor parties.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Voters over 60 gave much more support to the major parties, particularly the CDU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The incumbent CDU–FDP government lost its majority by a wide margin, taking 80 of the 181 seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] However, a prospective SPD–Green coalition came up just one seat short of a majority with 90 seats of the 91 required.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] There were four plausible majority coalitions: a grand coalition between the CDU and SPD (134 seats), a CDU–Green–FDP "Jamaica" coalition or SPD–Green–FDP "traffic light" coalition (both 103 seats), or an SPD–Green–Left "red-green-red" coalition (101 seats).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU aimed for a Jamaica coalition or grand coalition, while the SPD hoped, in order of preference, for a traffic light, red-green-red, or grand coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The prospect of a grand coalition was complicated by the extremely narrow margin of the election: both major parties took 67 seats in the Landtag, and the question of who would serve as Minister-President was disputed.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Rüttgers insisted he would continue in office since the CDU won more votes than the SPD, while Kraft insisted that she should take over given the harsh losses of the CDU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD first approached the Greens for discussions, with the intention of then seeking a third partner – either the FDP or Left, with a preference for the former.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] On the morning of the 14th, they sent invitations to both.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Left accepted, but the FDP declined, with leader Andreas Pinkwart stating: "The offer from the SPD and the Greens obviously lacks any seriousness, otherwise the Left Party would not have been invited on the same day. ...
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The traffic light and Jamaica are no longer coalition options." After the first meeting between the SPD–Green bloc and Left on the 20th, Hannelore Kraft announced that talks had been unsuccessful.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] She cited problematic sentiments about East Germany and a lack of willingness to take responsibility by The Left as factors.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD then invited the CDU to talks for a grand coalition, while the Greens withdrew in the expectation that they would remain in opposition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] After three rounds of meetings, the SPD withdrew from talks on 2 June citing a lack of compromise from the CDU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Kraft said they were unwilling to change policy or personnel, while Rüttgers insisted that only a few contentious issues remained.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The previous day, the FDP had reversed their position and announced they were open to talks for a traffic light coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The three parties met on 8 June, and again on the 10th for about ten hours.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The next day, the FDP announced that talks had failed: they had not been able to reconcile their positions, most especially with the Greens on education policy, and felt the demands of the SPD and Greens were too harsh.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] On 12 June, after a one-on-one meeting between Rüttgers and Kraft about a grand coalition, the SPD executive voted not to pursue further coalition options and instead withdraw into opposition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Kraft said that they would attempt to garner majorities for legislation on the floor of the Landtag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This was received poorly by the other parties, including the Greens, who called for a minority government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] On 17 June, the SPD reversed its position and Kraft announced that they would indeed attempt to form a minority government with the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Shortly before, FDP leader Pinkwart had told the *Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung* that the coalition between the CDU and FDP had run its course, and that his party would push for "majority decisions in the interest of the state" in the Landtag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Reportedly, the SPD leadership saw this as the effective end of Rüttgers' government, which had been operating in a caretaker capacity since the election, and strengthened the likelihood of investing an SPD minority government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Though they hoped for cooperation from the FDP, the party executive unanimously decided on 22 June to vote against Kraft in the investiture and oppose a red-green government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Since the SPD and Greens together held more seats than the CDU and FDP, they would be able to win so long as The Left abstained.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD and Greens did not consult The Left and rejected suggestions that they were relying on them, but once they FDP made it clear that they would vote against Kraft, they did tacitly require tolerance from The Left or their government would fail.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD and Greens quickly concluded a coalition agreement, with both parties ratifying it on 10 July.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Hannelore Kraft, proposed by the SPD and Greens, was the only candidate.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In the first ballot, she received 90 votes in favour, 81 against, and ten abstentions, suggesting that one Left deputy voted against.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The second ballot required only a simple majority.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Kraft was elected with 90 votes in favour, 80 against, and eleven abstentions.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The new Landtag met for its inaugural session on 9 June.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] By convention, the largest party nominates the presiding officer (President of the Landtag), but the tie in seats between the CDU and SPD made it unclear who had the right.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The two parties were also concerned that the selection of the president could affect the outcome of government negotiations.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They agreed to put off the question by exploiting a constitutional loophole: if no new presiding officer is elected at the inaugural session, the outgoing president from the previous term remains in office.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They convened the council of elders of the previous Landtag to remove the election of the presiding officer from the agenda of the inaugural session, claiming there were no applicants.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Outgoing president Regina van Dinther (CDU) thus remained in office and chaired the inaugural session.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] However, she had lost her seat in the election and resigned the presidency effective at the conclusion of the 9 June session.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The office thus passed to outgoing first vice-president Edgar Moron (SPD), who had also lost his seat; though he was no longer a member of the Landtag, he served acting president until 17 July, when Eckhard Uhlenberg (CDU) was finally elected.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2010-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This situation was harshly criticised in the *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung* by Patrick Bahners, who labeled it an act of "self-rejection" contrary to the principles of democracy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The **2017 North Rhine-Westphalia state election** was held on 14 May 2017 to elect the members of the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The incumbent coalition government of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and The Greens led by Minister-President Hannelore Kraft was defeated.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) became the largest party and formed a coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] CDU leader Armin Laschet was subsequently elected Minister-President.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This election was the last election in which an incumbent Minister-President was defeated until the 2022 Saarland state election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the previous Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU became the largest party with 33% of the vote.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The governing SPD and Greens suffered a 13-point swing between them, the latter losing half their seats.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The FDP achieved their best ever result in the state at 12.6%, and AfD debuted at 7.4%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Pirates collapsed to just 1% of the vote and were ousted from the Landtag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2017-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Left doubled their vote share to 4.9%, but fell just short of the threshold.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Germany on 26 September 2021 to elect the members of the 20th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] State elections in Berlin and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern were also held.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel, first elected in 2005, chose not to run again, marking the first time that an incumbent Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany did not seek re-election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With 25.7% of total votes, the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) recorded their best result since 2005, and emerged as the largest party for the first time since 2002.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ruling CDU/CSU, which had led a grand coalition with the SPD since 2013, recorded their worst ever result with 24.1%, a significant decline from 32.9% in 2017.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens achieved their best result in history at 14.7%, while the Free Democratic Party (FDP) made small gains and finished on 11.4%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) fell from third to fifth place with 10.4%, a decline of 2.3 percentage points.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left suffered their worst showing since their official formation in 2007, failing to cross the 5% electoral threshold by just over one-tenth of a percentage point.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party was nonetheless entitled to full proportional representation, as it won three direct mandates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW) was exempt from the 5% threshold and won 1 seat, the first time it held national representation since 1949.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With a fifth grand coalition being dismissed by both the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the FDP and the Greens were considered kingmakers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 23 November, following complex coalition talks, the SPD, FDP and Greens formalized an agreement to form a traffic light coalition, which was approved by all three parties.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Olaf Scholz and his cabinet were elected by the Bundestag on 8 December.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Irregularities in Berlin led to repeat elections in February 2023 (state) and February 2024 (federal).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the federal repeat election meant that the FDP lost a seat in the Bundestag, while 3 other seats were moved from Berlin to different states.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2017 federal election was held after a four-year grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Though the CDU/CSU remained the biggest parliamentary group, both it and the SPD suffered significant losses.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership, recognising the party's unsatisfactory performance after four years in government, announced that it would go into opposition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With the CDU/CSU having pledged not to work with either the AfD or The Left before the federal election, the only remaining option for a majority government was a Jamaica coalition consisting of the CDU/CSU, FDP, and the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Exploratory talks between the parties were held over the next six weeks, though the FDP withdrew from the negotiations on 20 November, citing irreconcilable differences between the parties on migration and energy policies.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Chancellor Angela Merkel consulted with President Frank-Walter Steinmeier, who implored all parties to reconsider in order to avoid fresh elections.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD and their leader Martin Schulz indicated their willingness to enter into discussions for another coalition government with the CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership voted to enter into exploratory discussion on 15 December 2017 and at a party congress in January 2018 a majority of the party's delegates voted to support the coalition talks.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The text of the final agreement was agreed to by the CDU/CSU and the SPD on 7 February, though was conditioned on the approval of a majority of the SPD's party membership.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 463,723 members of the SPD voted to approve or reject the deal from 20 February to 2 March, with the result announced on 4 March.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 78.39% of members cast valid votes, of which 66.02% voted in favor of another grand coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel was voted in by the Bundestag for a fourth term as chancellor on 14 March, with 364 votes for, 315 against, 9 abstentions, and 4 invalid votes, just 9 more votes than the 355 needed for a majority.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The new government was officially referred to as the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's final government was subject to intense instability.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2018 German government crisis saw the longstanding alliance between the CDU and CSU threaten to split over asylum seeker policy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Interior Minister and CSU leader Horst Seehofer threatened to undercut Merkel's authority by closing German borders for asylum seekers registered in another European Union (EU) country.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The split, eventually repaired following a summit with EU countries, threatened to bring down the government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following his party's historically low result in the 2018 Bavarian state election, Seehofer was replaced as CSU leader by new Bavarian Minister-President Markus Söder at a party conference in January 2019, while he retained his position as Interior Minister in the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In October 2018, Merkel announced that she would resign as leader of the CDU at the party's conference in December 2018 and step down as Chancellor of Germany at the forthcoming election, following poor results at state elections for the CSU in Bavaria and for the CDU in Hesse.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's allegedly preferred candidate for the party leadership, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, narrowly defeated Friedrich Merz, who had been a rival of Merkel around 2002 and had left politics in 2009 criticising her decisions and leadership.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A party convention to elect a new leader was scheduled for April but was repeatedly delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The election was held in January 2021, with Armin Laschet, incumbent Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, winning with 52.8% of delegate votes.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The other party in the coalition government, the SPD, also had leadership instability.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following their worst general election result since 1945, at the beginning of the new government the party elected Andrea Nahles as their leader in April 2018.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Nahles had already been elected leader of the SPD parliamentary group after the federal election in September when the party still planned to go into opposition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She was unsuccessful in improving the party's stock with the electorate as it continued to slide in opinion polls and was for the first time in history well beaten by the centre-left party Alliance 90/The Greens at the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She resigned on 2 June 2019, precipitating a leadership election for the SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Progressive candidates Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken defeated the more moderate candidates Olaf Scholz and Klara Geywitz, and were elected co-leaders by the party's membership.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Their election raised prospects of the coalition government collapsing and early elections being called, although Reuters reported that the duo would seek to achieve agreement from the CDU/CSU on increasing public spending rather than allow the government to collapse.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In August 2020, the party appointed Merkel's deputy Vice-Chancellor Scholz as its candidate for chancellor at the election, despite him having lost to Walter-Borjans and Esken in the party leadership election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Cem Özdemir and Simone Peter stood down as co-leaders of the Greens after the failed Jamaica negotiations, and Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were elected as their successors in January 2018.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Dissatisfaction with the SPD and the federal government saw a rise in Greens' polling numbers throughout 2018.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They scored record results in the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October and subsequently surpassed the SPD in public opinion, settling in second behind the CDU/CSU for the next three years.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party had its best ever showings at the 2019 European Parliament election, 2020 Hamburg state election, and 2021 Baden-Württemberg state election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They briefly polled in first place during two brief periods, first after the 2019 European Parliament election and again after the nomination of chancellor candidates in April 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left also underwent a change in leadership, with Katja Kipping and Bernd Riexinger stepping down after nine years as party co-leaders.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They were succeeded by Janine Wissler and Susanne Hennig-Wellsow at a party conference held digitally on 27 February 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler is considered a member of the party's left wing, formerly aligned with the Socialist Left faction, while Hennig-Wellsow is considered a moderate and part of the party's pragmatic wing.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both support their party's participation in federal government, particularly Hennig-Wellsow, who played a major role in the red–red–green coalition government of The Left, the SPD, and the Greens in the state of Thuringia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Germany uses the mixed-member proportional representation system, a system of proportional representation combined with elements of first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Bundestag has 598 nominal members, elected for a four-year term; these seats are distributed between the sixteen German states in proportion to the states' number of eligible voters.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Each voter can cast two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a state party list vote (second vote).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The second votes are used to produce a proportional number of seats for parties, first in the states, and then in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] If a party wins fewer constituency seats in a state than its second votes would entitle it to, it receives additional seats from the relevant state list.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can file lists in every single state under certain conditions, such as a fixed number of supporting signatures.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can receive second votes only in those states in which they have filed a state list.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] To qualify for proportional seat distribution, a party must receive more second votes nationwide than the electoral threshold of 5%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] This requirement is waived for parties winning at least three single-member constituencies.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As result of this waiver, parties have benefited on three occasions, such as the DP in the 1957 West German federal election and the PDS in the 1994 German federal election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties representing recognized national minorities are exempt from the electoral threshold.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As of 2021, these minorities are the Danish, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Under this rule, the 2021 federal election had to take place on a Sunday between 29 August and 24 October (inclusive), as the previous 19th Bundestag had held its first sitting on 24 October 2017.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The President of Germany sets the exact date for the election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 9 December 2020, President Frank-Walter Steinmeier ordered the election to be held on 26 September 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the fourth time since 2009, the 2021 federal election was observed by OSCE, providing four experts from three OSCE states.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Center for Monitoring, Analysis and Strategy (CeMAS) found that false claims of voter fraud had become commonplace on Telegram in Germany, with accusations against Dominion Voting Systems being common despite the company's technology not being used in German elections.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] CeMAS researcher Miro Dittrich said, "We have seen far-right actors try to claim election fraud since at least 2016, but it didn't take off.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The table below lists the parliamentary groups of the 19th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the election of Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Armin Laschet as federal CDU chairman in January 2021, he became the presumptive CDU nominee for the Union's joint chancellor candidacy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was challenged by Minister-President of Bavaria Markus Söder of the CSU, who consistently polled well among voters and had been discussed as a potential candidate since mid-2020.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As the contest intensified in March/April 2021, Söder was backed by the CSU as well as some state and local CDU associations, while Laschet received the support of most of the CDU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The two men failed to come to an agreement by the given deadline of 19 April, leading the federal CDU board to hold an impromptu meeting to break the deadlock.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The board voted 31 to 9 in favour of Laschet.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the vote, Söder announced his support for Laschet as chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 10 August 2020, the SPD nominated incumbent Vice Chancellor and Finance Minister Olaf Scholz as their lead candidate for the election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz, who served as Mayor of Hamburg from 2011 to 2018, unsuccessfully sought the SPD leadership in the 2019 leadership election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz was formally elected at a party conference on 8–9 May 2021, supported by 96% of delegates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD's lead candidates were chosen via a membership vote held from 17 to 24 May 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ticket of party co-chairman Tino Chrupalla and Bundestag co-leader Alice Weidel were elected with 71% of votes; they were opposed by the ticket of former German Air Force lieutenant-general Joachim Wundrak and MdB Joana Cotar, who won 24%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] 14,815 votes were cast, corresponding to a turnout of 48%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 21 March 2021, the FDP association in North Rhine-Westphalia elected federal chairman Christian Lindner as top candidate for the party list in that state.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] He was re-elected as chairman on 14 May, winning 93% of votes with no opponent.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The vote also served to confirm him as lead candidate for the federal election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left announced Janine Wissler and Dietmar Bartsch as their co-lead candidates on 2 May 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler was elected federal party co-leader earlier in the year alongside Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, who chose not to seek the co-lead candidacy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Bartsch had co-chaired The Left's Bundestag group since 2015, and was previously co-lead candidate in the 2017 federal election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler and Bartsch were formally selected by the party executive on 8–9 May, receiving 87% of the votes.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Due to their rise in national opinion polling since 2018, the Greens were expected to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Party co-leaders Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were considered the only plausible candidates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Baerbock was announced as chancellor candidate on 19 April.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both Baerbock and Habeck were co-lead candidates for the party's election campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 47 parties and lists were approved to run in the 2021 federal election, including the seven which won seats in the 19th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Of these, 40 ran party lists in at least one state, while 7 ran only direct candidates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In addition, 196 independent candidates ran in the various direct constituencies.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In the table below, green shading indicates that the party ran a list in the indicated state.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The number in each box indicates how many direct candidates the party ran in the indicated state.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In July 2021, the respective state electoral committees rejected the lists of the AfD in Bremen and the Greens in Saarland.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD list was rejected for formal reasons, while the Green list in Saarland was declared invalid due to a controversial nomination process, in which one third of the state delegates were excluded from the nomination convention.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both state parties filed motions against the rulings.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal electoral committee dismissed the motion of the Saarland Greens, while the AfD list in Bremen was permitted to run in the elections.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Green Party will thus not be eligible for the proportional vote in Saarland for the first time in the party's history.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal election was impacted by incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel's decision not to run again, and candidates to present themselves as the natural successor to Merkel.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2021 European floods, with at least 184 deaths in western parts of Germany, put the climate issue back on the agenda in July.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD called for "everything to be done to stop global warming," while the CDU/CSU wanted to "speed up climate protection measures".
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] By the end of July, 56 per cent of Germans believed that the floods made it "even more important than before" to combat climate change, and 73 per cent believed the government was not doing enough in this area; only the AfD's supporters were overwhelmingly of the opposite opinion.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following those events, six people under the age of 30 began a hunger strike in front of the Reichstag building at the end of August.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They demanded a sincere dialogue with the leaders of the main political parties before the elections and the establishment of a citizens' convention to decide on ambitious measures for the climate.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the deadly 2021 floods, while visiting Erftstadt on 18 July, the CDU/CSU lead candidate Armin Laschet was caught laughing on camera and making jokes while President Frank-Walter Steinmeier was speaking.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was heavily criticized, despite his apology saying: "It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it." Both the CDU/CSU and Laschet's ratings suffered heavily in opinion polls and the SPD took the lead.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the campaign, Scholz rejected tax cuts for the rich as immoral, pledged to "increase taxes on the wealthy, spend on cleaner technology and expand social programs", and a minimum wage increase to 12 euros.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] One SPD delegate was quoted as saying: "To prepare the ground for a robust and functioning coalition, you need to make sure that no one walks out of talks looking like a loser.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In its election manifesto, The Left called for abolishing NATO in favour of a "collective security system with Russia's involvement", to which Scholz said that this is an example of minimum criteria to govern which is not negotiable.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left's lead candidates stated that those demands are a tribute to the party's historic anti-imperialist roots rather than reflecting ambitions to govern at the federal level and a discussion on the future of NATO is also being led by centrists such as France's Emmanuel Macron.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party struck the anti-NATO demand from its immediate policy measures and Janine Wissler responded that foreign policy was more than NATO.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Gregor Gysi, a member of the left wing of the party, stated that such demands are more of a vision, are not to be implemented as soon as possible, and should not be seen as inflexible preconditions for a left-wing coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens see foreign policy differences with The Left as big as financial and debt disagreements with the FDP.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left joining the federal government would have broken a taboo due to being a democratic successor of East Germany's ruling party, and for its pacifist and anti-militarist stance, and could be seen as following examples in Spain and Sweden.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was seen as the more likely scenario but a R2G coalition, which would be favoured by the left-wing leadership and rank-and-file party members, was not excluded if coalition talks with FDP fail due minimum wage increase or the wealth tax.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time since 2002, the four major television broadcasters (public services ZDF and ARD with its regional networks, and commercial networks RTL and ProSieben/Sat.1) did not hold a joint television debate of only the major candidates from CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Separate debates were previously prevented by incumbent chancellor Merkel, but she did not run for a fifth term in 2021, and Armin Laschet represented CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens had only finished 6th in the 2017 election, but from mid-2018 to mid-2021 were ranked as 2nd in polls, even first in spring of 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Thus, with the traditional Two-party system of Union and SPD getting broken up and expanded to three on the federal level.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time, the traditional two-way duel debates became a three-way truel, dubbed "Triell".
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Additional four-way debates, in 2025 called *Quadrell*(quadrel), were held with leaders of the smaller parties that were part of the parliament.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Although the vote share of the South Schleswig Voters' Association (0.12%) was well below the 5% electoral threshold, due to its status of being representative of a recognised minority group (Danes and Frisians), an exception in federal law allowed the party to win one party-list seat.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbents are denoted in bold and followed by *(I)*.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In Berlin, vote casting and counting was not simple as the federal election was on the same day as the Berlin Marathon, the 2021 Berlin state election and a local referendum.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Federal Returning Officer felt compelled to request a report from the State Returning Officer Petra Michaelis.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In some polling stations ballot papers were missing or ran out and could not be delivered on the same day due to the Berlin marathon.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Ballot papers (of which there were 115 different variants in Berlin) and postal voting documents were also swapped.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Many votes were cast long after the official end of voting at 6 p.m, the last after 8 p.m. when the outcome was already being forecast.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] At least one polling station was closed due to missing documents.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In at least 16 Berlin polling stations, basic election data did not match (including impossible voter turnouts of over 100%).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 29 September 2021, Michaelis announced her resignation and that of her deputy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In 2022, the 2021 Berlin state election was declared invalid, to be replaced by the February 2023 Berlin repeat state election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Decision making on the federal level took even longer.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In late 2023, a repeat of the federal election was ordered in 455 of 2,256 Berlin precincts.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the repeat election on 11 February 2024 replaced the original result in those precincts, resulting in the overall result of the election being recalculated.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As a result of the repeat election, the FDP lost a seat in Berlin, resulting in the size of the Bundestag being reduced from 736 to 735 members.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD, Greens, and The Left each lost a seat in Berlin, while gaining one in Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, and Hesse respectively, thus keeping the total number of seats won by those parties unchanged.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] For the first time since 2002, the SPD emerged as the largest party in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also for the first time since 2002, the SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg and Saarland, where they defeated cabinet ministers Peter Altmaier and Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won all constituencies in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern for the first time, including Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I, the seat of outgoing chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] It was also the first time they won any single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia since 2005.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD had been written off by many political observers due to longtime internal quarrels and poor performances in prior elections, even those in early 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In the 2019 European Parliament election, they dropped to a historic low 15.8%, accelerating the decline of already deeply embattled and unpopular leader Andrea Nahles.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] When the unpopular and little-known SPD leaders Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken nominated moderate Olaf Scholz, whom they had unexpectedly defeated in the 2019 leadership election, as Chancellor candidate in August 2020, they were widely mocked.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD sat at a distant third place in the polls and stayed there until their sudden surge late in the campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] However, even at their historic poll lows around 14%, Olaf Scholz had a significantly higher personal approval rating than both his party and the other Chancellor candidates Laschet and Baerbock.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After the extreme personal unpopularity, resulting from gaffes and scandal, meant that first Baerbock and then Laschet floundered, the SPD took the lead, for the first time since early 2017, in the final stretches of the election campaign.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This surge also meant that some "paper candidates", a lot of them young, were unexpectedly elected to the Bundestag, for example Jan Plobner, Jakob Blankenburg or Fabian Funke.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That being said, the surge and eventual outcome of the election was mainly decided by older voters, who switched from the CDU/CSU to the SPD, which some attributed to Scholz being very similar in his calm and moderate leadership style to incumbent Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU had their worst result ever by far, eclipsing the previous worst of 31% in 1949.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] There was speculation that chancellor candidate Armin Laschet would lose election to the Bundestag; he was placed first on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list, and if the CDU gained overhang seats, that list would not be used.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Due to the CDU's bad performance in terms of single-member constituency seats, Laschet was elected to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The first time since 2005 that they did not win all single-member constituency seats in Bavaria, the CSU also had their worst result in history.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the catastrophic defeat were corruption scandals of several CDU/CSU politicians in spring 2021, some minor allegations even being brought against Laschet himself.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, Laschet was suffering from extreme personal unpopularity, even in his own state.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet did not have the incumbency advantage that helped moderately popular Merkel to win re-election three times, but still had to run on Merkel's legacy in voters minds.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This meant that the otherwise popular CDU/CSU platform of increasing digitization, reducing bureaucracy and moderate climate action were not taken seriously as his party had not addressed them in sixteen years of government in the minds of many voters.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In one infamous campaign moment, Laschet spoke of a "Wind of Change" in his closing statement in the first three way debate, which was widely ridiculed.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The contentious decision by the CDU establishment to have him run as CDU/CSU candidate instead of the much more popular CSU leader Markus Söder also played into this.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] During the belligerent internal selection process in spring, polls showed Söder faring a lot better than Laschet in the election, often higher than the 2017 result, and Söder was the preferred candidate of the base and the public at large.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Even fairly late into the election campaign, 70% of CDU/CSU supporters wanted to replace Laschet with Söder.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Söder publicly supported and defended Laschet, even on election night, but was accused of backstabbing Laschet's candidacy in order to become chancellor candidate in 2025.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet took responsibility for the result, but initially refused to resign in hopes of becoming Chancellor through a Jamaica coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The ensuing talks were plagued by leaks damaging Laschet and after Söder prematurely declared the talks to be over, both Greens and FDP decided to enter coalition talks with the SPD instead.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After intense pressure from his party and the public, Laschet announced on 8 October 2021 that he would step down but would moderate the next CDU leadership election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That leadership contest was the first to be decided by party members, who overwhelmingly chose conservative outsider Friedrich Merz in December 2021, after he failed in the previous two leadership elections, to Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer in 2018 and Laschet in January 2021.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was seen as a rebuff to the party establishment, who had backed Kramp-Karrenbauer and Laschet, both seen as being more moderate, aligned in both policy positions and leadership style to Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens got their best result in history, nearly doubling from 2017.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Their slump in the polls was largely attributed to a number of gaffes from and the personal unpopularity of Annalena Baerbock, though polls show that a lot of Green voters migrated to the SPD in the final weeks of the campaign to ensure the CDU would not form government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Though she won in the party-list, Baerbock lost in Potsdam – Potsdam-Mittelmark II – Teltow-Fläming II to SPD's Olaf Scholz by a large margin.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, though the Greens won 16 single-member constituency seats, all of them except Flensburg – Schleswig, the constituency of future Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck, were entirely urban constituencies.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens were also disqualified from running on the Saarland state list due to irregularities in the selection of list candidates.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens had, however, won only one seat in the Saarland in the previous two federal elections.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP had their second best showing since German reunification, gaining a few seats to maintain its fourth-place position.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was enough to make it a kingmaker alongside the Greens in coalition talks.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Like the Greens, they did well with young voters; among first-time voters, they received the highest vote share of 23%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, while they only marginally improved their result in the West German states, their more significant increase in support in former East Germany amounted to their best performance there in the party's history.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD lost seats and went from the third largest party and Leader of the Opposition to the fifth largest party in the Bundestag; however, they performed strongly in former East Germany, where they won 16 single-member constituency seats in Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, and Thuringia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the AfD lost vote share in Saxony, the stronger losses of the CDU still allowed them to place ahead of the CDU, becoming the most voted party in Saxony.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won the most party list votes in Thuringia, though only by 0.6%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for their drop in support include far less media attention, largely due to the open Chancellor's race, and large swaths of anti-lockdown and anti-vaccination voters, which the AfD campaigned hard on, voting for new parties like dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leader of the AfD faction in the Bundestag Dr.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Alice Weidel was widely ridiculed for claiming on election night that they surpassed their 2017 result if one added the results for dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Left had their worst showing since 2002, when it was the Party of Democratic Socialism, slumping from 69 seats in 2017 to just 39, or 4.9%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit parties with regional appeal (as is the case with the Left in the old East Germany), any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Apart from this symbolic defeat, their preferred government, a left-wing red–red–green coalition, did not have a majority in the new Bundestag, and the German financial market rallied as a result.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Vice President of the Bundestag Petra Pau lost her single-member constituency of Berlin-Marzahn-Hellersdorf by a large margin.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The seat had been held by The Left and its predecessor parties since the 1990 federal election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the massive slump were public quarrels in the party.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] These public feuds intensified after the election, for example, the convicted former head of government of East Germany Hans Modrow, who chairs The Left's "council of elders", denounced the party.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] From February 2022 onwards, the Russian invasion of Ukraine put a strain on The Left.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also, due to the irregularities during the 2021 elections in Berlin, affecting state level and federal level results, both elections were under ongoing scrutiny.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] According to court decision in 2022, the state election was repeated as a whole by the February 2023 Berlin state election, with losses for The Left.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A possible upcoming 2024 repeat of the federal election in parts of Berlin was a threat to the faction status of The Left in the Bundestag, and to 38 of 39 members, with only the direct seat gained in Saxony being not affected.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] With the Bündnis Sahra Wagenknecht establishing itself in October 2023 with 10 parliament members, the faction of The Left was dissolved in late 2023, losing funding and privileges by getting demoted to a group, or two in that case.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election was a watershed moment for candidates with a migration background.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In terms of representation of ethnic minorities, one source suggested that the Bundestag would have 24 new MPs with "Balkan" ancestry.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Its list included, however, largely people of Turkish ancestry who mostly have roots in Anatolia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW), a regionalist party only contesting Schleswig-Holstein representing the Danish and Frisian minorities in Southern Schleswig, won their first seat, becoming the first regionalist party to win seats since 1953.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Recognized minority parties are exempt from the threshold of 5%, which is how the SSW won a seat with 0.1% of the vote nationwide.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SSW last contested in 1961 and last won a seat in 1949.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They named a felt discrimination of Northern Germany as reason for them contesting the election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Stefan Seidler was seated as their Member of the German Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Seidler was offered to sit in the SPD parliamentary group as a guest by their leader Rolf Mützenich, but declined.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Minor parties did exceptionally well in the 2021 election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The left-wing satire party Die PARTEI had their best result ever, as did the Animal Protection Party and the regionalist Free Voters, which doubled their result and received 7.5% in Bavaria, where they take part in the state government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A few new minor parties emerged in the 2021 election, the most notable being the Anti-lockdown and Anti-vaccination dieBasis party, which received between 1 and 1.9%.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Team Todenhöfer, founded in 2020 by notorious former CDU Member of the German Bundestag Jürgen Todenhöfer, also first contested the 2021 election, running on anti-militarism and receiving support from pro-Palestinian groups, but only garnered 0.5% of the vote.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election also accelerated the decline of the far-right National Democratic Party, which only got 0.1% of the vote.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The NPD was at a time the most successful minor/fringe party, getting 1.6% in 2005 and entering various state parliaments in former East Germany.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A three-party governing coalition, with the FDP and the Greens joining either the SPD or CDU/CSU, was discussed as a likely outcome.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the grand coalition of the CDU/CSU and SPD could have been renewed, numerous representatives of both the CDU/CSU and the SPD ruled out this option before the federal election, during the campaign, and after.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On election night, SPD leader Scholz reiterated his goal to form a government, citing the fact that his party emerged as the largest in parliament.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] He expressed his intention to become chancellor and his preference for a traffic light coalition with the FDP and the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leading figures in the CDU/CSU such as Michael Kretschmer stated that since the CDU/CSU was knocked down to second place, it should not form the government.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP and the Greens, having won 210 seats between them, announced that they would talk separately before deciding on whom to support as a senior coalition partner.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens and the FDP held discussions for two days after the election.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 7 October, the two parties met with the SPD for the first round of exploratory talks, with a second round on 11 October.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 15 October, the SPD agreed to more ambitious climate targets, as pledged by the Greens.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 17 October, the Greens voted to enter formal coalition talks with the SPD and FDP.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The next day, the FDP voted to do the same.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 20th Bundestag was officially sworn in on 26 October.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 16 November, the general secretaries of the three traffic light coalition parties (SPD, FDP, Greens) announced that an agreement document was almost complete, with Scholz to become Chancellor, and that the details would be issued some time in the next week.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 23 November, an agreement for a traffic light coalition was finalised.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The three parties announced a number of policies, including plans to phase out coal energy by 2030, eight years ahead of the previous target, as well as lower the federal voting age to 16 years, raise the minimum wage to €12 per hour, and lower barriers to acquiring German citizenship.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Annalena Baerbock will become foreign minister, while Robert Habeck will head a new "super ministry" with responsibility for climate, energy, and economy.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Christian Lindner will become finance minister.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD convention voted 98.8% in favour of approving the agreement on 4 December, followed by the FDP with 92.4% on 5 December.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The results of the Greens membership ballot were announced on 6 December, with 86% voting to approve the coalition.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Scholz was elected as Chancellor by the Bundestag on 8 December, with 395 votes of 707 cast, with 303 votes against.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] An indirect presidential election (officially the 17th Federal Convention) was held in Germany on 13 February 2022 to elect the next president of Germany.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic and the high number of delegates, the meeting took place in the Paul Löbe House, spread over several floors, unlike its usual location in the plenary hall of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Frank-Walter Steinmeier became the first Social Democrat to be re-elected as president.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] The German Basic Law, the *Grundgesetz*, mandates that presidential elections must be held no later than thirty days before the sitting President's term ends, unless the presidency falls vacant prematurely.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] On 19 March 2017 Frank-Walter Steinmeier of the Social Democratic Party, who was elected by the 16th Federal Convention on 12 February 2017, entered office and started his first five-year term as president.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Therefore, the next Federal Convention could not convene later than 16 February 2022.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] The Bundestag's Council of Elders scheduled the 17th Federal Convention for 13 February 2022.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] The Federal Convention consists of all the members of the current Bundestag (736 members) and an equal number of state electors, allocated to the sixteen states of Germany in proportion to their population.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] The state electors are elected by the state parliaments.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] (A parliament diagram representing 1472 electors for the German president.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] As is common for the state-nominated delegates of the constitutional convention, a number of non-politicians - some of them celebrities - are nominated by various parties.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] During the 17th Federal Convention, virologists Sandra Ciesek and Christian Drosten are both among the members as is infectious disease specialist Marylyn Addo, all of whom came to broader public prominence during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] In Baden-Württemberg, the SPD and FDP (both in opposition at the state level) agreed to nominate a joint list with 13 members proposed by the SPD and 12 by the FDP.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Every member of the Federal Convention (members of the Bundestag and state electors, once they are elected by their respective state parliament) can propose candidates for the presidency.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] It is required that the President be a German citizen and at least 40 years old.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Every candidate has to declare their consent to running.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] Candidates can be proposed before the Federal Convention and (theoretically) during the convention before every ballot.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] If the president-elect is a member of a legislature or a government at the federal or state level, they have to resign from that office before the start of their term.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] A sitting president is not allowed to run for a third *consecutive* term.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/2022-german-presidential-election] None of the candidates were members of the Federal Convention themselves.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Pinkwart was born in Neunkirchen-Seelscheid, North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] After finishing his Abitur (A-levels) in 1979 Pinkwart took on an apprenticeship with Dresdner Bank in Cologne.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] He subsequently studied Economics and Management Science in Münster and Bonn, receiving his Diplom-Volkswirt in 1987.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] With his dissertation "Chaos und Unternehmenskrise" (chaos and a business crisis) he attained the title Dr. rer. from the Rheinische Friedrich-Wilhelms-University of Bonn.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] It was published as edition 116 of the series *Beiträge zur betriebswirtschaftlichen Forschung*.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Pinkwart's political career is closely knit to the FDP (Free Democratic Party).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] He joined the party in 1980, at the age of 19.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 1988 to 1990 he was part of the FDP's scientific staff and from 1991 onwards he was first secretary to the chairman of the FDP's parliamentary group in the Bundestag, Hermann Otto Solms.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Pinkwart's career in Higher Education began 1994 at the College of Higher Education in Düsseldorf, where he was professor of Economics and Management Science.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 1998 onwards a professorship at the University of Siegen followed, where Pinkwart taught Business Administration with focus on SMEs.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In 2002, Pinkwart succeeded Jürgen Möllemann as chairman of the FDP in North Rhine-Westphalia, an office he held until 2010.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2003, he also served as one of the national party's deputy chairmen under the leadership of Guido Westerwelle.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2002 to 2005 Pinkwart was a Member of Parliament (German Bundestag), where he was part of the FDP parliamentary group led by Wolfgang Gerhardt.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] He served as his parliamentary group’s spokesperson on the Finance Committee between 2002 and 2004 and later as the group’s spokesperson on the national budget.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2004, he also led the Bundestag group of FDP parliamentarians from North Rhine-Westphalia, one of the largest delegations within the FDP parliamentary group.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2005 until 2010, Pinkwart served as State Minister for Innovation, Technology and Research and Deputy Minister-President of the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, under the leadership of Minister-President Jürgen Rüttgers.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In this capacity, he was also a Member of the Federal Council (Bundesrat of Germany).
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Following the 2009 federal elections, Pinkwart was part of the FDP team in the negotiations with Chancellor Angela Merkel’s CDU/CSU on a coalition agreement.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] He led his party's delegation in the working group on education and research policy; his co-chair of the CDU/CSU was Annette Schavan.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] At the beginning of 2011 Pinkwart became a senior research fellow at the American Institute for Contemporary German Studies (AICGS) at the Johns Hopkins University, Washington D.C.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] His research project as fellow focused on the roles of universities as entrepreneurial hubs and engines of innovation in the U.S. and Germany.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2011 he served as Dean of HHL Leipzig Graduate School of Management and the first holder of the Stiftungsfonds Deutsche Bank Chair of Innovation Management and Entrepreneurship.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Following the 2017 state elections in North Rhine-Westphalia, Pinkwart was part of the FDP team in the negotiations with Armin Laschet’s CDU on a coalition agreement.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] He led his party's delegation in the working group on economic affairs and energy policy; his co-chair of the CDU was Hendrik Wüst.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] From 2017 to 2022, Pinkwart served as State Minister for Economic Affairs, Digitization, Innovation and Energy in the government of Minister-President Armin Laschet.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In this capacity, he was also one of the state's representatives on the Bundesrat, where he served on the Committee on Foreign Affairs; the Committee on Economic Affairs; and the Committee on Urban Development, Housing and Regional Planning.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Pinkwart was nominated by his party as delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2022.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In November 2022, Pinkwart announced that he would resign his parliamentary seat and leave active politics.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Following the 2010 state elections, Pinkwart ruled out a center-left coalition between the SPD, the FDP and the Green Party even though the three parties would have been able to achieve a majority in the state parliament.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] On energy policy, Pinkwart is widely regarded to be a critic of the country’s energy transition as envisioned by former chancellors Gerhard Schröder and Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In 2017, he held that he wanted to preserve the use of fossil fuels and place greater restrictions on where wind turbines can be built.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] In 2018, he demanded at least 10 billion euros ($11.5 billion) in structural support if coal-fired power stations are phased out.
[src:andreas-pinkwart/andreas-pinkwart] Pinkwart is married and has two children.
